description: After surviving a terrifying night lost in a forest, four mismatched teenage boys return home to find that things aren't quite as they left them.
tags: ['title directed by female', 'live action fantasy']
synopsis_with_character_names:
Four Year 10 students - Andy, Felix, Jake and Sam - are forced to buddy up for an orienteering exercise in the rugged Bremin Ranges, on the outskirts of their hometown, Bremin. The boys are from very different friendship groups and do not really get along, so when they are expected to collaborate they are not happy. Halfway through the orienteering course, they decide to take a shortcut that very quickly gets them lost.

Andy, Felix, Jake and Sam must put aside their differences and work out how best to survive the night. As a freak lightning storm takes hold, the boys' fertile imaginations run amok. But there is really something out there. A ferocious, snarling thing stalks the boys from the undergrowth.

For Andy, a diehard nerd stifled by his family's over-protectiveness, getting lost is an opportunity to prove himself as a man of action and follow in the footsteps of his hero, Bear Grylls. Being an outsider is nothing new to Goth Felix, who is more than willing to embrace the weirdness of the situation. Alpha jock Jake uses a bullying demeanour to cover his vulnerability, while golden boy Sam - for whom nothing ever goes wrong - doesn't see the seriousness in their predicament.

The boys finally manage to make it out of the forest - alive and triumphant - with help from eccentric bushman Roland. Upon their return to Bremin, the boys discover that no one seems fazed by their disappearance. Where are their anxiously waiting families? Where are the TV crews? Something has changed.

Felix is shocked and delighted to discover that his younger brother, Oscar, is no longer wheelchair-bound, but Oscar doesn't seem to know who Felix is. The others also return to their homes and families to find that things are not as they were. Has something happened to Bremin while the boys were lost in the forest? Or has something happened to the boys?

description: The guys continue to investigate their "disappearance" by searching the school records, Sam finds clues of his existence from their usual timeline and finds his doppelganger.
tags: ['title directed by female', 'live action fantasy', 'carving on a tree']
synopsis_with_character_names:
The boys' survival instincts kick into gear as they scavenge for food and set up a home in the derelict shack. What proves more difficult is coming to terms with their loss of identity. It's one thing to be forgotten, but it's starting to look like they never existed.

Andy, Felix and Jake break into Bremin High searching for proof of themselves in the school records. All they find is the dismaying confirmation that no evidence exists of them ever being students there. Then the upside dawns: nonexistence means absolute freedom. To celebrate this realisation, the boys run riot in the gym, unaware of a security camera filming their destructive fun.

Meanwhile, Sam finds a romantic carving made by himself and his girlfriend, Mia, only a month before. Buoyed by what he considers to be tangible proof that he exists, Sam searches for Mia to confirm his identity. His hopes are crushed when Mia doesn't recognise him. Nevertheless, the presence of the carving gives the other boys hope that there is still some semblance of them in the world. Perhaps the effects of their 'erasure', if that's what it is, can be reversed? Jake convinces Sam to show Mia the proof in the hope that it will jog her memory.

Sam returns to Mia and shows her a photograph of the carving. When Mia reveals that she made it with her boyfriend, Sammy, Sam is stunned to find himself facing off against a smarmy younger version of himself. A desperate Sam confronts his mother, Dee, but like everyone else, she still doesn't recognise Sam at all and, worse still, suffers a violent physical reaction to him. Gutted, Sam returns to their hideout to join his new, mismatched family.

If these setbacks aren't enough, the 'thing' that stalked the boys in the forest makes a scary return.

description: The guys are trapped in a storm that leaves strange markings outside their hideout. Felix and Sam go to find protective charms against what caused the freak storm, Andy and Jake try to catch what they think left the markings.
tags: ['title directed by female', 'live action fantasy']
synopsis_with_character_names:
Huddled inside the hideout, the boys find themselves held captive by a freak storm. It is a terrifying night.

When the boys emerge the next morning, they discover strange configurations of debris scattered around their hideout. Andy's search for a scientific explanation and Felix's belief that magic is at play causes conflict and the group part ways: Andy and Jake head to Lily Lau's restaurant to obtain bait to trap the panther which Andy believes has caused the markings; Felix and Sam head to Arcane Lane in search of more mystical answers.

Using Sam to distract Phoebe, Arcane Lane's mysterious proprietor, Felix discovers an old tome that identifies the hideout configurations as a demonic centrifuge. Disturbed, he buys an amulet for protection - but will it work?

Andy's ninja aspirations fall flat when he is sprung and entrapped by his hostile family while trying to pilfer the bait. Despite his best efforts, Andy fails to convince his father, that he really is his son from another dimension, brought here via a wormhole. His Grandma Lily declares Andy to be the ghost of her unborn grandson. Jake helps Andy make a hasty escape before the police are called.

Andy desperately continues to search for other possible answers, only to convince himself that he and the other boys are actually in a state of unconsciousness. Driven to test his new theory, Andy sets out in search of a stimulus powerful enough to jolt them all back into a state of consciousness. Andy decides to throw himself in front of the local school bus in an effort to "wake up". The other boys race to stop him in time.

description: Welcome to Graceland - a prime piece of real estate that was seized from drug lords and now serves as an undercover residence for agents.
tags: ['guy wears a too small tee', 'undercover', 'hazing', 'beach', 'chore', 'swimwear', 'execution', 'drug trade', 'drinking', 'bare chested male']
synopsis_with_character_names:
Welcome to "Graceland," a new USA crime drama about five undercover Feds-- DEA, FBI, Customs-- picked to live in a swanky house in Manhattan Beach, CA named after the abode of Elvis Presley himself. (So dubbed because the drug dealer who previously lived there was obsessed with the King.)

We will mostly be seeing the series through the eyes of FBI newbie Mike Warren who is the newest addition to the house. He joins ringleader/senior agent Paul Briggs, fierce female FBI agent Charlie, friendly Iceman Johnny Turturro, DEA gal Paige Arkin, and seemingly menacing FBI guy DJ Jakes.

According to the show's opening scroll, the series is based on actual events that happened at a house of this kind.

We see Mike as he graduates from the academy and hears a rousing speech about walking into the battlefield of the real world. This is cross cut with a deal going down by a harbor somewhere. A drug deal happens, the man buying tests the heroin- seemingly in his arm-- but then the small piece of fruit he was using hidden in his elbow crook to inject the drugs falls out. The dealers make him for an agent and he is shot and falls to the ground. A female member of the selling team, clearly an agent, Lauren, his partner, freaks as he is shot and all parties speed away.

This was agent named Donnie, who Mike is replacing. (Donnie's not dead but he's down for the count.)

Briggs is told to pick Mike up at the airport by Gerry, the overseeing boss, but he sends Johnny so he can go surfing. (Mike has been doing immersive Spanish training on the plane.) Johnny gives him the lay of the very sexy, laid-back land. (Lots of chicks in bikinis.) He then brings him to the house. Their covers: Briggs says he's a tae bo instructor and Charlie says she's a trust fund kid.

Inside the house Johnny shows him the "chore wheel" and informs him wherever it says "Donnie" it's now his job. The phone room where all government calls are made. And then to his room which is still full of Donnie's stuff. Lauren is very grumpy with him, protective of her shot partner.

Jakes-- who is working on a bird smuggling ring-- arrives home and as Mike tries to greet him he gets angry that Mike is drinking his orange juice and ate his cereal. Briggs wakes up and Mike tells him he's honored to be training with him. He's very eager to get going. Briggs' first job for him is to have him do his chores so he can get used to the whole "undercover" thing. He then grabs a bottle of rum and wanders off. Mike can't believe this is the "brilliant" Briggs he has heard about.

Charlie, looking like a bag lady/addict stumbles around a crack house, collecting evidence and helping with a baby. She heads back to Graceland and is the next person to give Mike a hard time. When she enters he thinks she's a burglar and they face off with guns. He learns there are "no guns downstairs."

Donnie is in a safe house, recuperating. Lauren chats with him and tells him the Russian and Mexicans want him dead and she tells him about the "new guy" Mike. She tells him it's not Graceland without him and to hurry up and get well.

The next day Briggs awakes to a spotless kitchen. Mike is serious about the chore wheel. Briggs takes him for a surfing lesson. It does not go well right away. There is a lot of wiping out.

As he gets to know everyone and what they're working on, he's struck by how laid back Briggs is. Charlie says he used to be more button downed but a few years back and something happened and he took a leave and he came back all Zen-ned out. She doesn't know what.

Lauren is on a rampage to get the guys who shot Donnie, and so he gets sent on a deal with a low level dealer. On the way to his first deal he also hears tell of a convoluted cover story that involves Briggs being in an actor who sometimes plays a cop in the movies who is undercover as a male hooker called "Sunset Bust." It was a story he used to get out of trouble with some dealers, he even pulled out his badge and said it was a prop for the movie-- a low budget film. They decide that Mike is also in the movie, and he plays Briggs' brother-in-law.

He heads to do the deal. Of course, he immediately starts using this cover story because he is nervous. The guy doesn't have any money but Mike tries to save the op when the guy says he has merch to exchange for the drugs. He shows him a truck full of 15,000 pairs of jeans. This is not a good deal. But he makes it anyway. They arrive and arrest both of them. Except that at the police station they walk the dealer into Mike and his cover is blown.

A Russian lawyer shows up to help Felix, the guy Mike busted, and who knows he's a cop. Except that guy is not Felix's lawyer, he's a Russian mobster.

Briggs looks over Mike's file and sees that he requested a D.C. assignment and was first in his class but was given an "emergency" assignment at Graceland.

Mike, Charlie, Briggs, and Johnny hangs out and bond. Mike is nicknamed "Levi." (For the jeans.) Mike tells DJ how he got his nickname. He asks DJ about himself and the protectiveness of his OJ. DJ just says Mike got him on a bad day and turns out to be a nice dude.

Felix's lawyer tells him that he best not talk to the Feds and just in case his family will be staying with them. Felix is freaked and tells the Russian lawyer that Mike is his brother-in-law.

It turns out Felix does have a white brother-in-law. So Mike has to go back to the police department and pretend to be Felix's brother-in-law, Frankie, complete with fake scar and track marks and withdrawal symptoms. The Russians are bailing him out. Briggs says they'll get him to kill someone so they have him in the "family." He tells Mike to play along in order to get Felix's family free. They have a reporter that will print up a fake homicide and everyone walks away.

Mike passes the audition with the Russians thanks to quick help from the gang back at the police station. Here's the scary twist though: they want Mike to kill Donnie at the safe house. Mike and Donnie face off and discover who each other are. Mike explains it's his first day. Donnie and Mike say hi to the gang back at the police station through the wire Mike is wearing. Mike squeezes off a bunch of shots into the floor and leaves. The Russians want him to get in the car, they pull a gun, Briggs shows up and saves his ass. He kills one of the Russians claiming he saw the gun even though Mike knows he didn't. But, he does know that Briggs saved his life.

They watch the next morning as the news reports of the nabbing of the Russian mobsters. Felix gets his family back.

Briggs and Mike are debriefed and are cleared for a clean shooting. They are commended for their good work.

Later that night at a bonire with the gang and they have a toast to their success. Briggs commends Mike and says he's an undercover agent now and his "lies are his life" which means girls and family. Mike asks how he keeps from going crazy. Briggs says "who says I haven't."

Mike gets a call and here's the twist: it's the FBI boss who was speaking at Mike's graduation and his actual assignment is to investigate agent Briggs and will the fact that Briggs saved his life affect that? Mike says nope. The FBI director says if he keeps that attitude he'll make deputy director one day. Briggs comes up and says he noticed in his file that Mike asks for D.C. and got this instead. Briggs wants to know if he knows why. He claims he doesn't.

description: When ongoing investigations clash, Briggs and Mike seize the opportunity to tilt rival gangs against each other while Mike learns that undercover life comes with many moral complications.
tags: ['animal in episode title', 'dog in episode title', 'contraband', 'nightclub', 'smuggling', 'handcuffs', 'therapy', 'beach', 'bare chested male']
synopsis_with_character_names:
Briggs and Mike take a walk down the boardwalk and Briggs tells Mike to figure out wh he is in this new world. He's just known as Paul, a dude who digs motorcycles, rum, and tae bo.

They hook up with Johnny and head to Hector's taco food truck. While there a kid robs the food truck and decks Hector and Mike takes off after him. Briggs tells Johnny to stop him. They try to point out to him that he's undercover and he can't go chasing petty criminals in the place where they live, he'll blow his cover.

The next morning he awakes at six and makes his bed like a good boy scout and drinks his OJ and works on his grip strength and heads for a run on the beach while listening to his Spanish-language lesson tapes. He runs past Charlie doing the walk of shame. At breakfast Charlie says she was cultivating an informant who likes Jagermeister. Jakes says he has to go work on his bird smuggling case. Mike promises not to try to make a mistake like yesterday again.

Johnny opens the mail. Mike has to go to a psych eval in the wake of the Russian mobster shooting. He also gets a case, working with Briggs but Briggs thinks he's too green to be squeezed onto one of Briggs' cases. He argues to be put on the case of a drug and gun runner named Bello. Briggs wants to give him a case with "training wheels."

Jakes, pretending to be Jamaican goes to get a shipment of illegal birds. The "order" is screwed up. The guys he's meeting with trap him in the back of the truck and he calls a team to rescue him. They pull a crate out of the back of the truck behind the birds and it's full of "cop-killer" bullets.''

Back at Graceland, Lauren is taking down photos from the Russian mob case. She's been pulled from the case and she told them that she has to go back to the Ukraine to care for her sick mother. Briggs tells her that Donnie, her partner, is not coming back. Briggs tells her to let Donnie go. She doesn't want to let him go.

Mike heads down to the FBI office to see Dr. Juan Badillo for his "psych eval." They talk about what got him hooked to the FBI. His grandfather was a crime scene photographer. Mike wants to fight evil. The doctor asks if he's disappointed in being assigned undercover to Graceland instead of D.C. like he wanted. He said he was disappointed at first but he loves the house and the agents. He calls Briggs "complicated." Mike realizes that Badillo is not a shrink and he's actually there as his "control officer" to talk about his investigation of Briggs. Mike wants to know why he's investigating. Badillo says for now he just needs to get close to him and that if they help him with Briggs he can write his own ticket out of Graceland and back to D.C and the fast track. He says it won't be easy. Badillo says that's why they chose Mike.

Mike confides in Charlie that he wants to be on the Bello case. Charlie says Mike has to charm him and bring him something. They need to offer Bello something that will make a splash. Mike gets it in his head to offer the way illegal bullets that Jakes discovered. In the meantime, she asks him for a favor back. She needs him for a covert op. They head to their "undercover closet" full of various wardrobe and make-up to dress him up as her tough boyfriend.

They head to a karaoke bar to meet up with Paige, who is onstage singing. Mike starts drooling over her. Paige is pretending to be a bad guy's girlfriend. They all head to ladies room. Paige jokingly calls him Levi as Charlie works on crushing birth control pills into the bad guy Bobby's drink. Apparently, this will keep him from getting an erection. It works and he's embarrassed and kicks Paige out. She doesn't like the case because Bobby won't talk business in front of her. Briggs says he has a connection with Bobby's crew and will try to help.

Mike offers the cop killer bullets to Briggs to offer to Bello. He says he'll pretend to be a Marine, fake sell the bullets to Bello's lieutenant, arrest him and flip him. Briggs says he'll think about it. He does, and decides it's a go. Jakes doesn't want to give up the bullets because it could come back to haunt him. He trades Mike for two turns on the chore wheel.

They set up the op and meet with Bello's lieutenant Eddie. They test out the bullets on teddy bears with cop body armor on them. But they're bad shots and Mike goes alpha on them. He takes the gun from Eddie and points out the bullets are longer and heavier then they're used to and they need to aim just under their targets. He blows the bears away and makes his point. Eddie is impressed and they make a deal which means they will finally be able to meet Bello. They have made a sufficient splash and are bringing him something he wants.

Over a bonfire on the beach, Johnny dramatically tells the tale of gunslinger Mike to the other agents and pretends to shoot them all. Briggs seriously congratulates Mike. He asks over his psych eval. Mike says it was standard stuff but he's going to make it a weekly visit. Briggs seems a little suspicious of this. They toast their merry band of misfits.

The next day they go to make the sale. They get the money and the bad guys take off. Mike is confused as to why they're not arresting them since that was a plan. Briggs says that was Mike's plan. Mike is freaked out that the cop killer bullets will now be on the streets. Briggs has a plan. They stop for hot dogs and Mike is confused. Mike calls and leaves a message with Badillo. He goes back with the hot dogs. Briggs asks if he trusts him. Mike says no. Briggs tries to explain that he's been in with these guys for awhile so he knows that Eddie always makes the same getaway plan and that he will be in this spot in no time. The bad guys show up and are intercepted while what seems like other bad guys. They are Paige's guys with Bobby. This is how Briggs is helping her. Bringing Bobby something. Mike asks now what? Briggs says they are going to buy their bullets back with the money they just got from Eddie from selling the bullets. They then arrest Bobby (and Briggs and Mike.) Pretty ingenius. Mike asks why Briggs didn't tell him about the plan. Briggs notes when he asked if he trusted him, Mike said no and asks if who he called at the food truck. Mike says he was just checking messages. Briggs wondered if he was tempted to call into the bureau on the plan. He says he was tempted but he didn't. Briggs noted if he had he would've crashed the whole plan. Briggs notes this would've been bad. Mike says anything could've gone wrong. Briggs notes that it didn't, they busted Bobby and got closer to Bello and it was a good day and their side won.

Mike goes to see Badillo and tells him he can't underestimate Briggs. Badillo pumps him up and says he's smarter than Briggs and to work it out.

Briggs and Mike go to meet Bello in a suitably creepy industrial/warehouse environment. Briggs comes up behind Mike and puts a gun to his head and says "who have you been talking to?"

description: Briggs calls on the house to help Lauren with her case against the Russian Mafia and Charlie gets into some hot water when her C.I. proves unreliable during a dangerous drug deal.
synopsis_with_character_names:
We pick up right where we left off with Briggs pointing a gun at Mike's head asking "who you been talking to?" He disarms Mike. It's a set-up. The lights flicker on and Bello and his crew emerge asking why Briggs is pulling his gun on his own man.

Briggs explains that since Bello's bullets got jacked by Bobby and then Bello requested a meeting with them and when they showed up he could make out Bello's men pointing guns at them he did the math: Bello thinks they sold him out and the only new face around here is Mike's so it must've been him. Bello praises his quick thinking while Mike protests that he didn't say anything to anyone. He throws the suspicion on Bello's lieutenant Eddie, who always did the same "heat run"-- tricky getaway moves-- every time. It's clear they plan to torture the guy but Bello believes them and welcomes them with open arms. They're in with the boss.

On the ride home they exult in the adrenaline rush of playing the game. Briggs is proud of him and tells him to stand up and scream his lungs out and he does and feels good. Mike admits he was afraid Briggs was going to kill him and he was just making it up as he went along. Briggs says he rocked it.

They debrief over drinks at Graceland with Johnny, Charlie, Paige, and DJ.

Lauren goes to confer with Briggs about the Russian mob job. Donnie was transferred to Miami. She thinks if she takes down another member of the mob Donnie can come back. She tells Briggs the Russian mobster has something in the works for the next day and they try to work out a plan. Briggs bring in the other FBI folks, Johnny and Mike. It's a car thieving job.

Mike tells Badillo about Bello and Briggs pulling the gun on him. He asks again why he's investigating Briggs. They think he might be skimming cash. Badillo asks for more details in the future.

Charlie goes to see her informant Whistler, a meth head. He's working on a dollhouse or his niece. She wants to know what's up. He has a score for her, a drug dealer who's desperate and he wants to help Charlie get him off the street. He claims he's not high. She tells him to set up the job. He asks for his usual 20 percent ahead of time and he needs the money now because he's getting kicked out. She denies him and tells him to stay out of trouble.

They set up on the highway with spike strips to catch the truck with the cars. They realize the truck is running too light to have the cars and hey kill the mission. Lauren runs into the road to stop the truck, identifying herself as a DEA agent, convinced there is something on it thereby screwing up the mission. The truck is empty. Briggs tells her she's done since the mob driver has now seen her face. She claims she can fix it. He tells her it's over.

Mike and Johnny and tell DJ and Paige about what went down over lunch and beers. They talk to Mike about how he can never break his cover. They can't speak freely because one of Paige's guys she's working on is on the bar. She told him she's a pharmaceutical rep. Johnny is always either a pilot of a photographer. DJ plays bass in a band that no one has ever heard of.

Paige goes back to see her mob buddy. He tells her about the DEA/FBI stop. He says the job is not off. The guy's driver is right in the other room. He sees Paige leave and all he can say is "nice ass. He doesn't see her face.

Mike tries to work a woman as a aspiring pro golfer and Briggs comes in and the woman Mike is hitting on skedaddles because she thinks Briggs is an astronaut, who she blew off.

Mike goes back to the table and joins them. He leans on Briggs' credit card on the table, gets the imprint of the number on his hand and takes a picture of it.

Charlie and Whistler meet with the drug dealer who is impressed with their stuff. Charlie asks to see the money and then Whistler messes thing up by asking for more money. Charlie tries to override him and says let's do this. The bust goes down. Charlie and Whistler play the game yelling at each other "you set me up." As they're arrested, Charlie berates him for the rogue move.

Lauren comes home with a black eye. She tells him the Russian mobster did it because he caught her sniffing around. She apologizes but says she had to know she wasn't crazy She saw the Lojacked cars in the warehouse so they have their evidence.

Charlie goes to see Whistler and tells her she can't use him as an informant anymore because he's too risky. She tells him to get his life together. He is desperate and tells her he's screwed. She says he's getting a check for $100,000 and wonders how that's screwed. He asks what he will do without her. She tells him he needs to grow up and will get his check tomorrow. He asks if she at least fought for him. She says she did.

Everybody goes to hit the Russian mob warehouse and get the cars. They blow the door and a firefight ensues. There are way more guys then expected. They overtake them and arrest Lauren's Russian mobster. They pull him aside and Briggs "talks" to him. Giving him payback for punching Lauren. When he notices his knuckles are clean, he realizes Lauren played him, saying the mobster hit her to make the job happen.

Later they toast at the bar. Johnny shows off his scar from the fight. Lauren opted out of the party.

Paige tries to get Mike to hit on a girl at the bar Mike says he's not up for it. Says Paige goes to talk to the girl on his behalf. Her name is Abby. While they chat some people hit on Paige and Charlie and Briggs decides to literally hit on them. He works out his aggression from the job.

Paige and Briggs work out that Lauren's story doesn't add up and realize that if the Russians put Lojacks on the cars they stole they could put one on her and if so she's leading the, now angry, Russians back to Graceland.

Apparently, Mike and Abby spent the night talking as they walk along the beach the next morning. She's an aspiring lawyer about to take the bar. She's spending the summer in California for her last gasp of freedom. She says Paige told her at the bar that of all the guys there Mike was the most "real." Abby asks if Mike is "real." They kiss.

He heads home and Paige buttonholes him to go work something out. To do this they play Frisbee on the beach. They pretend to lose it under a car, Lauren's. They find the Lojack.

Charlie drives Whistler to a house and says it can be his. It's a serious fixer-upper but he's a great carpenter and they both know he can fix it. They walk through it and he can already envision what he would do with it. She gives him the realtor number and the check and she tells him to call him, give him the check, and the house will be his.

Lauren comes home angry saying she is being kicked out of Graceland. Briggs says it was a self-inflicted wound like everything else going on here. He says he knows she liked to him and almost got Johnny killed and put the whole house in harm's way. He is livid that she played him. She says she did it for Donnie and she had to do something. He points out that she had to get him to do something. He says all is not lost,she's still DEA and if she puts in for a transfer she may just get Miami and there will be an agent there happy to see her. Briggs, always with the plan.

Mike sends Briggs' credit card number through the system to look through his purchases. He flags a purchase at an auto parts store. He heads over there and shows him Briggs' picture and what he bought, a GPS tracker. Like the one on Lauren's car. Mike figures it out and goes to Briggs with his "theory" that someone else put the tracker on Lauren's Jeep. Briggs admits that he did it because she endangered them all. He says if Mike is going to be good at this job there has to be dispassion except when it comes to protecting Graceland. He says he would do it to Mike.

Charlie drives by the house she showed to Whistler and a Hispanic family has apparently bought it.

description: Despite Briggs' hesitations, Mike gets recruited by a Nigerian drug lord to teach gang members how to shoot well, while Paige recruits Jakes and Tuturro to go undercover with a flirtatious and dangerous female pot farmer.

synopsis_with_character_names:
Paige makes a drug buy and busts the pot dealer. It's amazing weed and so she knows that there are bigger fish swimming around.

Charlie tells a story about her great, great grandmother saving a fugitive in Naples and they fell in love and kept their famous Ragu recipe in the family. She is making it for the house for "sauce night" and says it will be ready in three days.

Mike is texting with Abby and is busted by Johnny and Charlie. He claims she's not his girlfriend and knows he can't date. Charlie says they can date they just can't get too close.

Briggs and Mike set up a new meeting with Bello, SoCal's primary heroin supplier.

Paige shows Charlie and DJ the weed and they think that some of the legally allowed pot farms grow more than necessary and then flood the market with the extra for a little cash on the side. Paige wants to set up a meeting with the dispensary dealer, who once had a big crush on DJ. But he can't set up a meet with her as an undercover dealer since his cover with her was someone with ties to Latino gangbangers so they decide to send Johnny instead since he's Mexican. Charlie covers him with convincing (airbrushed) gang tattoos.

Briggs and Mike go to meet with Bello, who did a number on his right hand man in the last episode when he thought he betrayed him. Bello only wants to talk to Mike, who sits down with him a restaurant. His cover remains that he's a Marine. After his impressive marksmanship the last time they met, Bello wants Mike to teach his men how to shoot. When Mike doesn't recognize the phrase "WQB" at first they get suspicious of him but then he remembers the nickname for the phrase was "pizza box." This gets Bello off his back, and the gun out of his gut. Mike says he's in.

Charlie is still at work on her sauce. (It takes three days.) Briggs enters and informs her that Mike is now sitting down with Bello, a guy Paul has been chasing for years. He's both jealous and worried. Charlie says he has "quarterback syndrome," that he thinks his team mates can't win without him. She tells him to focus on getting the championship as opposed to the credit.

DJ and Johnny go to meet the weed dispensary lady, who may have had a crush on him, but also was a hardcore criminal and murderer. DJ wants to get the job done quick and easy. She gives him a big hug and asks Johnny his story. He pulls a bunch of character-appropriate attitude and walks away almost blowing the whole deal. DJ asks her to give him another shot and promises Johnny will behave. She invites them out to the farm the next day to see if they can make a deal.

Mike is going through the Bello files and he tells Briggs he wants to get him back on the case. Briggs pumps him up. Mike says he was told to "pretend" to train Bello's men. Given that Bello burned out his associate's eyeball, Mike doesn't think "pretend" training is going to work. Briggs promises to call HQ and assure them that they're in control and Mike needs to be serious.

The next day he heads out to train the men while the Graceland gang and other back-up listens in nearby. His men are former gangbangers and drug runners who competed with Bello. He essentially forced them to join him or face the alternative.

Mike begins the training with assembly and shows off his own skills. Bello tells him men to follow Mike's instructions.

Meanwhile, Johnny and DJ head to the pot farm with Paige and a back-up team following behind. The weed lady shows her the farm, it's not all weed, some of it is vegetables. She grows the weed in the barn. She continues to hit on DJ and they reminisce about old days. They talk about fireflies. DJ is anxious to see the harvest. She says she can't show them until the morning. She says she made them come to see if Johnny would grow on her. Johnny starts to flirt with her and she responds, seemingly. Paige is listening in and doesn't think weed lady is going to make the deal and wants to call it off. DJ says he has somewhere to be. Johnny says he can stay. Johnny thinks he's not only going to get laid but is going to make the deal happen. DJ says she's dangerous, Johnny counters that he's dangerous.

Mike calls Abby and apologizes for not calling lately. She's out with friends. He asks her out to dinner for the next night. But then he remembers Charlie's Ragu sauce and offers to take her to drinks instead. He is then jumped by Eddie, Bello's right hand man who is missing an eye. He's suspicious of Mike and he wants to know who he is. Mike disarms him, rather easily, and dismantles the gun to boot and tells him to never bother him again.

Mike made a heat run back to the house and Charlie and Briggs want to bring him in, since Eddie's a liability. It will make it look like Eddie is in fact betraying Bello. They have Paige pretend to be Bobby Moy's girlfriend again and Charlie tells Eddie that the rumor is he gave up the bullets. They leak word to Bello that Eddie is selling him out. Charlie offers him a bus ticket to Flagstaff. Eddie knows he's being set up but he takes the ticket because he knows his death warrant has been punched. Mike is upset about this but Briggs points out that Eddie punched his own ticket when he signed on two work with a criminal mastermind who pours hot lead in people's eyes.

Johnny wakes up and shakes the weed lady off of him. Unfortunately, when they ere sexing it up the night before he also smudged off a bunch of his fake tattoos on her sheets. He goes to the barn and starts taking pictures right around the time she wakes up and notices the black ink on her sheets. She confronts him with two men in the barn, all three with guns drawn on Johnny. Paige and DJ arrive and when he goes to check out the house he is dragged into the barn by one of the gunmen. The weed lady is very angry, assuming DJ has flipped. But when she finds his walkie talkie she realizes he's a cop. But before anything can happen, Paige barrels into the barn with the truck and hops out, quickly dispatching one of the men. The weed lady grabs DJ as a human shield and tells Paige to drop her weapon or she'll kill him. Paige drops her gun but as the weed lady is distracted, Johnny whacks her in the head with a nearby bucket, saving the day.

Back at the house, everyone enjoys Charlie's Ragu. Briggs gives Mike his blessing for going on the date with Abby. But then, of course, that's when Bello texts Mike and says he wants to see him and keep training. Bello wants to speed things up and use a human target. They drag out a bloodied and bowed Eddie. Eddie claims Mike is working with the Feds who made up the story about Bobby Moy and that even though he was going to flee he didn't tell the Feds anything. Bello asks Mike if he's working with the FBI. Mike says no. BEllo asks for Mike's gun. Eddie tells Mike he's going to take his eye. Bello says this is going to end one of two ways. He hands Mike's gun to Eddie and whispers in his ear. Eddie cries, trains the gun on Mike and then reverses and puts the gun in his own mouth and pulls the trigger. At first Briggs and the back up team think it's Mike and starts to move out, but then he says something to alert them he is still alive. Mike is, justifiably, freaked out.

He then goes to meet Abby at the bar. He is dazed and out of sorts. He says he saw an accident in which someone died. She sweetly tells him to go home saying he won't be good company. He heads home and all the sauce is gone and it's his turn to do the dishes. He is shaken. Briggs enters and offers to give him a hand with the dishes. He also notes Charlie left him a plate. Mike says he wants to be alone and tells Briggs to eat it since he missed "sauce night" too. Briggs tells him '"it's just sauce."

description: While Mike gets deeper into Bello's organization by trying to convince him to hire him as his bodyguard, Briggs and Charlie resume their former identities as a sexually-charged couple to get intel on a mysterious drug supplier called Odin from a drug dealer names Quinn.

synopsis_with_character_names:
"Graceland" - "O-Mouth" - July 11, 2013

Mike is still feeling depressed after watching Bello's man kill himself so Johnny and Paige drag him to the beach for a little touch football to cheer him up.

When they return Mike is stunned to see Charlie and Briggs "shooting up." But of course, it turns out they're just practicing for an undercover job. They use hemoglobin which is safe. Everyone advises that Charlie should exhibit a little more "O-Mouth" when she is pretending to have the high hit her.

Briggs and Charlie pretend to be a couple-- Katie and Eric-- and go to meet with their guy Quinn. They are using him to get to a higher up named Odin. (We also learn that Briggs and Charlie actually once really did get it on.) But as they are finishing up making plans to meet the big man, Charlie's former informant Whistler shows up. (The one who bailed on buying the house and getting clean after she cut him loose.) Charlie hops on Briggs' lap and starts making out with him so Whistler won't see their faces and blow their cover.

Mike goes to his handler Badillo and again asks why he's investigating Briggs who, although clearly unconventional, appears to get the job done and sincerely care about both his fellow Graceland housemates and pursuing justice. Badillo says there are good reasons. Mike says he's earned the right to know them. (If he tells them we don't see it.)

When they get home, Charlie is worried that Whistler made them. Briggs tries to reassure her and then tells her just to suss him out. She tells him she's done with Whistler. As they talk Paige and Johnny discuss whether Charlie and Briggs are about to hook up again. She bets it will, he says no. Loser pays the winner's bar tab for a week.

Mike runs into Abby at the bar. He mentions to Johnny that he never told her a cover job. He goes to chat with her. Johnny told her that Mike was a pilot. Mike goes with it.

Charlie goes to see Whistler and says she was worried about him. He swears to her that he's clean. She buys him a warm shirt. He thinks she wants to start using him for cases again but she says she just wants to make sure he's okay. She calls Briggs and says they're good and learns that they're on to meet Odin.

Mike walks with Abby on the beach. They run into Mike's beach dog and Abby suggests getting him a bath. He goes back home and Paige and Johnny give him a hard time that Abby wants to fix him and tame him. Mike thinks they're wrong.

Mike meets with Badillo who shows him a report that seems to speculate that they get less drugs than they expect to net from his busts and they think he's reselling the drugs to fund his rainy day account or trading it for intel. Mike suggests bringing him on Bello as a test almost since he has the potential to bring in an insane amount of drugs. Or steal them, notes Badillo.

Mike continues to train Bello's men and tells them that they need a few more months, Bello doesn't want it to take that long.

Mike goes to Briggs to talk about getting closer to Bello's drug dealings. Briggs tells him to take his time and work his cover. Mike wants to speed things up. Briggs tells him to offer to be his new bodyguard. Mike also discovers that Bello digs old westerns and hopes to use this to his advantage.

Briggs and Charlie go to meet with Quinn at an airport hotel. Quinn is running late so they get cozy and chat about the time that they hooked up. She calls them young, crazy kids.

Quinn shows up and is annoyed that Johnny is the valet, claiming he knows all the valets and he leaves, too paranoid to go in to the hotel.

Charlie and Briggs realize they're in a holding pattern and order room service. Charlie says she told him why she hooked up with him because he was a myth and wants to know why he hooked up with her. He says she is hot, beautiful, smart, kind and they agree the sex was mind-blowing. So they decide to have some more, much to Johnny's chagrin, who is listening in until Briggs turned off his watch. They come close to doing it but think better of it. But then they turn on some porn and turn on the watch again to make Johnny believe they did it so Paige will win the bet.

Mike meets with Bello who asks which of his men has the most potential. He tells them they're all a little skittish since Eddie's death. They chat about the movie and this seems to endear him to Bello. They go to a store to get more movies with the actor from the film Bello likes. He talks about how he likes this guy in particular because he's a cowboy who fights for himself. They get into an altercation with an employee and Mike shows his loyalty to Bello.

They go to Bello's and watch the movie. Bello says Mike impressed him. Mike offers to be his bodyguard. Bello says he likes him and likens him to one of the characters in the film and accepts his offer. Bello asks about what Mike is willing to do, to drive him, to jump at a moment's notice. Bello takes a call and Mike snoop around Bello's office, gawking at his calendar. He gets back to his seat in the nick of time.

Mike reports to Briggs that he's gotten closer to Bello. He tells him about seeing the name "Bigfoot" on Bello's calendar. It's a code name for bringing drugs in by submarine. Briggs is impressed with him.

Johnny confronts Briggs and Charlie and they pretend that leaving the wire on was an invitation to him. Johnny gets all weirded out as they come on to him. They come clean and have a good laugh. They realize they need to use Whistler to salvage their deal with Quinn.

She goes to Whistler and sets it up. He calls her wasted and tells her it's all set and to come over now. He passes out while talking to her.

Mike meets with Abby who got the dog all cleaned him up and took him to the vet. They release him back on the beach. He relishes telling Paige and Johnny that she let the dog go and doesn't want to tame him either.

Briggs and Charlie head to Quinn's. They discover Whistler is dead. When Quinn calls them out on not using his stuff-- saying this is what undercover cops do, since they are not allowed to actually take drugs-- Briggs tries to abort the deal. But Charlie, smarting from losing Whistler, takes Quinn's drugs and actually shoots herself up. There is sufficient "O-Mouth" when the drugs hit her.

description: Mike convinces Bello to steal from the most powerful drug cartel in Southern California and calls on Johnny's unique underwater skills to help.

synopsis_with_character_names:
"Graceland" - "Hair of the Dog" - July 18, 2013

After her using to prove she wasn't a cop in front of the dealer Odin, Charlie is a wreck. She apologizes profusely to Briggs, who brings her provisions to a safe room. She doesn't remember much, other than feeling great after shooting up and Briggs pulling her out. She feels like Whistler died for nothing and she blew it. He tells her the only thing she needs to worry about is getting better and says she'll be sick for a few days. She's at one of his CI's apartments. She tearfully says she wants to go home. He says she can't go back to Graceland because if the bureau catches wind of it she will be done and that he brought her there to save her career and that it will be their secret. She thanks him.

A group of Feds led by Johnny nabs a sub running drugs. Johnny and Paige head for the sub, mindful of booby traps. Johnny doesn't find anything, no drugs at all. But they're glad they're taking the sub out of commission anyway.

Mike is now ensconced as Bello's bodyguard. Bello's buddies are mad about the sub bust. He tells Mike that the drugs are actually in a torpedo which the guys on the sub let loose when they're caught. Mike suggests that he and Bello go and find the sub themselves and cut the cartel out and make the 20 million dollar payday. Bello tells him not to get too big for his britches. Mike says he knows a guy that could help them find it. Bello is listening.

Briggs and Johnny give Mike a hard time about boning up on westerns to get in with Bello. They heard his plan on the wire and they liked the idea but are angry that he improvised in the moment. Johnny suggests he be their fake "guy who knows something about subs." He's going to pretend to be a SEAL. Briggs reminds him that vouching for someone in Bello's world carries consequences. Mike claims he's not worried.

Mike brings his plan to Badillo, who likes it because it's busting both a dealer and putting the drugs on a silver platter for Briggs to steal if he's dirty. Mike asks if this will get him back to D.C. Badillo says it's not about how fast he gets back but getting back in one piece.

Charlie is toughing it out at the safe house, throwing up and sweating. She notices a locked door. Johnny calls her and she says she's still sad about Whistler. She says she's on a case in Fontana. She tells him she's fine. Johnny reports that he and Charlie have to come in and give their side of the Odin debacle the next a.m. at 9. She doesn't think she can make it but tells him she'll see him. She realizes she's between a rock and a hard place.

Mike has a date with Abby. She wants to go to his place but he says his room mates are messy. She feels like he's hiding them from her and says she wants to hang out, at least with Paige since she owes her an apology for introducing her to Mike. He says okay.

Briggs brings Charlie her clothes but is worried they'll be able to tell. She begs him for a solution. He offers her one in the form of "hair of the dog." She thinks he's crazy to have her go in there high. He promises it will get her through and then they can get the junk out of her system. What's scaring her is she actually wants it. He loads it up and says she doesn't have to do it. She does it. He says "welcome back."

Mike introduces Johnny the "SEAL" to Bello. (Johnny explains that the came close to becoming a SEAL but couldn't hack the SEA part and ended up being shipped to Iraq instead.) Bello is skeptical. Johnny plays the part and keeps saying things are classified. Johnny says he's not interested and takes off and Bello relents and tells him the story but says they don't have a transponder frequency to go on but other people looking for it do. He negotiates a fee of $20,000. He explains his plans to find it and says he's on the case.

Briggs takes Charlie to meet her boss with Johnny. Briggs says she looks okay but tells her to be careful as he's coming down, not to fidget, etc. She sasses that she knows about playing a cover.

Charlie and Johnny meet with the boss. She's a little argumentative but seems straight enough. She does starts to fidget a bit. Johnny comes to her defense and takes the blame. Charlie tries to argue this since it goes on Johnny's record but he takes the hit, and also takes her fidgeting hand under the table. He knows.

They go to lunch and she spills. He is upset that she was high during the evaluation. She says whatever it takes to save her career. Johnny knows Briggs knows and he tells her he doesn't care about anything he just wants her to come home and help her get better. He tells her he loves her. She says she loves him too.

Mike and Abby hang with Paige and a random dude at the Drop. Paige claims she's a spin instructor. Her date is a deejay. The guy is her "case," a drug dealer. Mike is not happy and lets Paige know. Mike tells her that Abby thinks this is a real date. She says "real" dates are not possible with what they do.

As Abby and Mike leave she tells him that the deejay is a drug dealer. He wonders if they should tell Paige. She thinks Paige knows since she acts different around him. She says she would never do that and hopes he wouldn't either. He says he acts different: better.

Johnny and Briggs debrief on the Bello situation, with the help of the military actually tracking the torpedo. Johnny confronts him about Charlie. Briggs says he told her he wouldn't and what's done is done.

Briggs and Johnny go to get familiar with "Johnny's boat" and talk more about the Charlie situation. Briggs explains he had to do something. Johnny notes he covered for them both. They find the torpedo, it's booby-trapped. Briggs wants to abort, Johnny says he can defuse it. Briggs says he doesn't need to be a hero. Johnny says he is a hero.

The next day he wetsuits up. Bello asks if he's sure it's there. If it isn't Johnny says he'll give Bello 20 grand. He heads down. He reports back that he sees the torpedo. Bello tells him to hurry. Bello has one of his guys train a gun on the surfacing Johnny. He says they have to kill him because he'll talk with his drinking buddies. Bello calls it his final classified mission. Briggs hears all of that and tells Johnny to tell them that the torpedo is booby-trapped to buy time. Bello offers him Johnny's share. Mike says it's his friend. Bello says he is his friend now. Mike says he wants to do it if it's going to be done. Bello begins musing about what he's going to call his new boat. Suddenly, an explosion rocks the surface. Bello grabs Mike and screams in his face about how much money he just cost him by Johnny screwing up and asks why he shouldn't send Mike down there too. Mike say she was about to shoot his friend for him, for goodness sakes. Bello apologizes saying he lost his head and expresses condolences for Mike's loss. They motor away in the boat.

Briggs heads back to the office and calls Briggs in a panic asking where he is. He then sees Johnny, totally relieved, hugging him hard. Johnny is touched and tells him they knew about the bomb and can't believe Briggs didn't tell him. Briggs enters and Mike punches him. Briggs says he called an audible and they won so he needs to calm down. Johnny simply detached the explosive from the torpedo and set it off to fool Bello...and Mike. Mike notes he was about to waste everyone on the boat. Good thing he didn't.

They pull out the drugs and Johnny notes that they could've packed in at least twice as much which raises Mike's antenna, wondering why they didn't (and if some is missing.) Briggs says it's the biggest haul he's ever seen. Mike wants to bust Bello now for intent but Briggs wants to let it play out a little while longer. Johnny notes that Briggs had possession of the drugs between the mission and arriving at the office. Mike watches him leave with a bag and follows him to a rundown apartment building. It turns out it's an NA meeting. He sees Mike in the doorway and says to the group, and Mike, "Hi my name is Paul and I'm a heroin addict."

Johnny welcomes Charlie home and says he's going to take care of her. She promises she won't be shooting up in an alley and to shoot her if she does. He says he's glad to have her back.

description: Dark secrets are revealed when Charlie decides to tell the house that she used heroin undercover. Briggs is finally forced to come clean to Mike, but just as Mike thinks his investigation is coming to a close, Briggs has a darker secret up his sleeve.
tags: ['therapy', 'loyalty', 'drug trade', 'false identity', 'theft', 'contraband']
synopsis_with_character_names:
"Graceland" - "Goodbye High" - July 25, 2013

We pick up right where we left off, at the 12-step meeting where Briggs announces that he's a heroin addict. Mike enters the room and eyes the bag that Briggs brought with him as he speaks about telling the truth.

At the end of the meeting Briggs unpacks the bag and it's a new coffee maker for the meetings. He and Mike take a walk by the beach. Briggs explains his story which we see in flashbacks.

A few years back he was working undercover in San Diego on a cartel. He was young, ambitious and in love. (He won't say who the girl is.) His training officer Umberto had worked his way into the cartel family. They found a dead body of a potential dealer that was mutilated. The killer wasn't found and Briggs was pulled off the case but Umberto stayed. Briggs went to Mexico alone against orders. But when he got there he was attacked and never discovered who turned on him. He says going there was the dumbest thing he's ever done.

He was captured and tortured by the man that mutilated the bodies code name "Jangles" for the keys around his waist. They shot him up with heroin and he gave it to him every day. They didn't ask him for any information. It lasted two weeks. He admits that it felt good. Then they stopped and abandoned him in the desert. He doesn't know why they did it and then let him go. He figured they did it as a way to stick it to the bureau but he kept it to himself and no one knows but him, the support group, the cartel and now Mike. He says he's been clean for awhile. Mike asks what they do now. Briggs says it's time to go home. "Just like that?" asks Mike. Briggs says Mike will either tell or he won't but all Briggs can do is keep moving forward.

Meanwhile at Graceland Charlie is feeling better as Johnny takes care of her. He wants her to sleep it off but she wants to work on arresting Odin. Johnny wants to do it. Charlie says she shot heroin twice and won't do it again. Johnny asks what it was like and asks if he tried it would he understand. She says he would. She insists on going back to work.

Jakes is working on a case of toy robots that were used as drug mules. Johnny wants to give one to his cousin. Jakes calls him cheap.

Mike and Briggs come home and claim they were driving Bello around all night.

Later, Mike walks in on Bello's drug operation. They are trying to stretch their supply by cutting it with a dangerous chemical since their supply is down since the loss of the torpedo. Mike challenges him on cutting the drugs, Bello takes issue with this and tells him to be careful since it was his fault they lost the torpedo so cutting the drugs is really his fault.

Mike meets with Badillo and tells him the torpedo tell and that it was impossible to tell if Briggs was stealing drugs. Mike wonders aloud if Briggs is actually doing this. Badillo claims he would be happy to hear that Briggs isn't a criminal. Badillo gives him a gift, it's a crime scene photo that Mike's grandfather took. He caught himself in the reflection. Badillo knows it's hard being away from family and thought he'd want a piece of him.

Johnny and Page and Mike and Abby meet at the bar for a hang. She has to go but she has Johnny snap a photo of them on her phone. Then Paige pockets the phone because it's dangerous for her to have a pic of an undercover agent. Mike is mad. They tell him to break up with her, to say his "ex" came back into the picture. He doesn't want to lie. Paige notes that he's been lying to her since day one.

Jakes goes to see his ex Cassandra and drop off a robot for his son. She says he can't give it to him. He knows. She points out that he wanted it this way and that Daniel doesn't even know him as his father. He gives her the robot to give to him. Jakes is sad.

Charlie goes to see a low level dealer and pretends to want to buy the good stuff that Odin had. She goes to see several dealers many who claim they've seen him, but none really know the guy.

Mike and Briggs throw around a ball in the living room and Mike is making the case for arresting Bello now. Briggs says they don't have enough info on the guy to bring down all those around him. Charlie comes in with her lack of info. Briggs strikes on the idea of having Bello -- who needs drugs-- to reach out to find Odin via Briggs to draw Odin out and get them both.

Mike brings the proposal to Bello, to choose a new supplier even though that means double-crossing the cartel. Bello says Briggs has 24 hours to set up a meeting or they'll hit the streets to hold up low level thugs and steal their drugs.

Briggs goes to talk to the dealers that Charlie went to to find Odin. Using Bello's name doesn't seem to be helping.

Paige shows Mike how to handle heroin and its works while Jakes works on a new CI with regards to the drug smuggling robots.

Briggs returns home and says he's succeded in setting up a meet with Bello and Odin. Charlie and Briggs talk about keeping secrets. She wants to tell the house. Briggs says she should keep it to herself. Instead she tells them. Johnny looks uncomfortable and admits he knew but it wasn't his place to say. Mike consoles her. Briggs is unhappy with the confession. Jakes hugs her.

Mike and Paige decompress about Charlie. Paige is DEA and says every day from now on she'll be checking Charlie, they have to watch each other's backs. Mike wonders what would happen if one of them truly became addicted. Paige says they'd help each other but that an addict can never be trusted.

Jakes is at a bar and he strikes up a conversation with his potential new CI. They chat about their gang tattoos. Jakes claims he had his removed. The guy got out after getting shot in a drive-by and surviving, it was a miracle. They share a whiskey and a chat. The guy says he fell for his nurse and moved her to be with her and her kid. And then we realize that this is the guy Cassandra is dating and that he is not trying to make him a CI at all. He shows Jakes a picture of his kid with pride and notes that the "real" father never comes up. The guy leaves. Jakes is sad. (This is a very "Jakes is sad" episode.)

Charlie chats with Briggs who is mad at her. She asks what his problem is. He says now if anyone ever asks from the bureau if anyone in the house has done drugs, the others will have to lie, she gave them no choice. He says her secrets are her burden and his his and they should leave it at that.

Mike and Badillo meet and rats out Briggs going to a NA meeting and says he doesn't know if he's currently using but he's trying to get better and he tells the story about the cartel. He wants Badillo to help him because he thinks Briggs is a great agent and he deserves it. Badillo says they'll help him. He tells Mike to write it up. Badillo assures him that if this means that his investigation to Briggs is over he'll go back to the East Coast.

Jakes comes home a little drunk and talks to Mike about breaking up with Abby. Mike asks for advice. Jakes says to stay with her. He notes that everyone sees Graceland differently. Briggs see it as his castle, Charlie as her family. Jakes sees it as "just a damn house." Mike says he hears that. Jakes tells him to find a way to keep Abby from finding out and to remember that Mike won't be living there forever.

Abby and Mike meet on a beach and she complains about her ruined phone being found at lost and found. He asks if she's excited to get back to her life on the east coast. She says if he wants to break up with her since the summer will be over soon he just should. He says he might be headed back to the east coast too and he doesn't want to break up with her. They kiss.

Briggs waits on the pier for his meet-up. Bello arrives. Paige, Mike, and Johnny listen/watch nearby. Charlie sits on a bench nearby texting. They pick out people from the crowd and bet on who it might be. Bello asks why Briggs wasn't able to deliver Odin. Paul says "who says I wasn't?" He clasps Bello's hand and give shim a packet of drugs. He claims he is Odin. (The others can't hear this conversation.) Bello and Briggs walk down the pier and he tells him that Mike doesn't know and the only ones who need to know are Bello and Odin/Briggs. And if that changes Briggs/Odin is out. He tells Bello he can maintain his current supply levels at 85 percent of his cost. They shake hands. Bello leaves. Charlie arrives and tells him his "watch went dead' with the listening device. Briggs tells her they didn't miss much and walks away with a smile.

description: The newly formed Briggs-Bello alliance is tested when members of the Caza Cartel head north with a deadly ultimatum. During the aftermath, Mike is forced to push his own limits for the good of the case.

synopsis_with_character_names:
"Graceland" - "Bag Man" - August 8, 2013

Mike and Briggs debrief and Mike tells him Bello told him he made the deal with Odin. Briggs complains about being shut out. They note the next big shipment is tomorrow so maybe they'll get lucky and catch him.

The next morning Briggs awakes at 5:30 and meditates and works out. He then heads out to the apartment where he stored Charlie while she was detoxing. In the closet that was locked, he walks into a crawl space full of bricks of drugs and the stickers that are "Odin's mark." He leaves them in a gym bag in a locker in a gym and texts Bello the location. Mike gets the money from Bello, switches the bags and tells Briggs to meet him there. He retrieves the bag and the FBI guys sweep the bag for evidence of Odin as Briggs watches. Mike delivers the drugs to Bello's assembly line, which is hot girls in their underwear wearing face masks divvying up the drugs in bags with Odin's mark. Then Briggs and Mike watch street level dealers sell the drugs. The whole process from nearly beginning to end which will net Bello and Odin nearly 2 million dollars.

As they watch the deal go down, Mike complains about how hard the job is. Briggs swears they're going to get him and that Odin will make a mistake. Mike notes that they found Briggs' DNA on the bag.... and that they also found Mike's own DNA and says, with a smile, that so far they're the only one making mistakes.

Mike gently teases Abby awake in bed. They kiss. He gets a text from Charlie saying they need him to look at security footage. She wants him to beg off. He says he can't. She starts asking questions and asks if he's seeing someone else. He says he doesn't have a secret girlfriend. She wants to know why she hasn't seen his house then. She says it's time for the "exclusive" talk. He says this guy at work that is like the brother he wished he had has a substance abuse problem. She hopes he reported him. He says he did but he loves the guy but he feels like a rat. She says he did the right thing and anyone who knows him would know he's not a rat.

Mike heads home and lies that he wasn't with Abby and that he was with a rebound. She says she has her own undercover heroin case to work on that night.

Jakes and Johnny work out at the gym, staking it out waiting for "Odin" to come get the money. Jakes complains they have the whole place covered by cameras and they could be watching from home. Charlie does just that. Mike watches with her. None of the money has been picked up. Briggs comes in and says maybe Odin doesn't care about money, noting they don't know anything about him.

Jakes and Johnny switch their stakeout to the car outside the gym. Johnny asks about things being weird in the house. Jakes says he worries about his own problems. Johnny says they're friends. Jakes says not to get it twisted and this isn't his family.

Briggs and Mike have a conversation about Briggs' confession. He says he hasn't heard anything from the bureau and thanks Mike for keeping his secret and that he knows secrets are a burden. Mike asks if it's hard to be around all this heroin. Briggs says it is but having Mike around keeps him honest. Mike notes honesty is a hard thing to come by. Briggs agrees.

Mike calls Badillo and asks what's going on. He then makes another drop of drugs to Bello at the abandoned bank they are using as HQ. He pulls Bello aside and says they might have a security issue. He asks Bello how he can protect him from someone Mike doesn't know what he looks like. Bello says he's willing to take the risk. Just then gun men come in and shoot up the place. They kill everyone, including the girls divvying up the drugs. Mike and Bello take the three men down. Bello tells them to take the bodies with them so they can tie up loose ends.

They take them to the warehouse and Bello starts to torture one to get info out of there. The hitman being tortured is from the cartel. Mike calls in. Briggs tells him he has two options: they can roll in right now and save the cartel hitman's life, nab Bellow, but blow nabbing Odin. Or Mike can save his life and preserve their ability to get Odin. Charlie is mad, since it's clear is Mike right on the edge, he can't take hearing the guy being tortured. Briggs says he gave Mike a choice. Mike enters the room where the guy is being tortured. The hitman says that cartel is sending a message if that Bello comes back to them for drugs all will be forgiven. Bello says you don't send a hit squad to negotiate a truce and then he chops off the guy's hand. Mike flinches. Charlie and Briggs overhear all of this. Mike says to send the hitman back as a message. The hitman says they're all dead now, that the real hitman "Jangles" is coming to kill them all. Bello commends him on his plan. Mike pretends to be happy about all of this.

At the beach Charlie notes to Briggs that Mike saved the guy's life and they preserved the Bello connection but he's probably scarred for life. Briggs notes that they now also know that the cartel is moving on Bello which is progress in his book. Briggs says the cartel is the real enemy and that's what he wants. Charlie says he always has to push it too far. Mike arrives and Charlie gently touches his face and says she's happy to see him and hugs him. Briggs asks if he's really okay. Mike says he doesn't feel anything. Briggs says it will hit him later. Mike asks him if this was really all about getting to "Jangles" -- that he had him let Bello torture the guy because he knew he had information on Jangles. Briggs tries to reassure and Mike says he doesn't want to be played by Briggs and leaves him.

Mike heads to Abby's and she knows something is wrong. He says people around him keep getting hurt. She asks if he's responsible. He says yes, for some of it. She says he then needs to take some responsibility that he always has a choice. She starts to get upset and he tries to comfort her. He invites her to Graceland. She notes that he's told her there's rules about that. He says he's not in a rule-following mood.

Johnny, Jakes, and Charlie wait outside the gym in the car, she tells them the story of Mike and the torturer and Briggs. Charlie "borrows" Johnny for a little while.

Briggs sits in the CI apartment and contemplates shooting up.

Charlie says she wants to go check on Briggs because she thinks something is wrong. Johnny agrees that something is up. Charlie brings up the theory that Briggs is Odin. Johnny doesn't like this at first but agrees. Charlie says they're not stabbing him in the back and she brought him to be the devil's advocate. They get to the door and he hears them as Charlie tries to pick the lock.

Mike shows Abby around Graceland which she says is like walking into Anthropologie.

They enter and notice the drugs on the table. They poke around. They find the closet and it's unlocked now. Briggs is sweating it out on the other side of the wall.

Abby wants to see Mike's room and he shows her but tells her to be quiet. He shows her the room. He notices a gun on the dresser and throws his coat over it quickly. She notes how nice it is but is quite Spartan. She notes that he doesn't see the space as permanent. He says part of him wishes it was because he loves the people. He asks if she still thinks he has a secret girlfriend. She says no. he goes to the bathroom and she notes the crime scene photo and opens the door and sees Paige with a gun. Paige sees her and says her dad is one of those guys who thinks single girls should have guns. Paige pulls Mike aside and says she's she'll cover for him and to get her the hell out. Abby picks up their coats and sees Mike's gun and asks who he is. She freaks out and says it's clear that he's been lying to her. She declines his offer of a ride home and kisses him goodbye. She says to call him if he ever figures it out. Paige is livid saying he just risked everything. He says it's over and he was sick of lying to her. Paige says everything he told her was a lie. Mike said he could feel safe with her. She says that's what Graceland is for. He says everyone has secrets there. He notes that Briggs breaks the rules all the time and gets away with it and he breaks one and it blows up in his face. Paige notes he needs to know which rules to break.

Mike brings another bag to the FBI to sweep and says they'll never catch Odin this way. Briggs tells him to stick to the plan. Mike calls an audible telling Bello he went to the drop and that there were no drugs there. He goes back to Briggs and Charlie and they argue this will force Bello and Odin into a meet. Briggs says Bello will think Mike stole the drugs and that he just risked this case and his own life.

Briggs goes to his closet and gets dugs. Bello calls and says they need to meet. Briggs says he'll text him the details. He hauls out a ton of drugs and throws them on the bed.

Charlie, Johnny, and Briggs stake out the potential meet spot. Briggs texts Bello a new locale and Charlie follows him on foot. Briggs sends Johnny off to follow a "stolen car." Mike asks if Briggs wants back up and Briggs says he can handle it.

Bello goes into the changing room of a store and moves aside the mirror and walks through a hole in the wall. Briggs and Bellow meet and Briggs says the cartel got to him. He hands Bello the keys to the apartment saying there's enough drugs there to hold him for a couple of months and to keep paying him in the same installments.

Charlie goes into the changing room and finds the hole in the wall as Johnny sees Bello exit a different store. Charlie heads through the hole, and Mike and Johnny enter from other points and Briggs is trapped. Briggs jumps Mike from behind. They tussle. Briggs manages to stun him with a chokehold without him seeing him. He fires a shot. Charlie and Johnny run in and find Briggs over Mike. Briggs claims that Odin just ran out and that he might have shot him. Mike awakes and Briggs asks if he saw him. Mike says no.

The next day at breakfast Johnny tells Jakes he was right that it's best to mind your own business in this house. Johnny commends Jakes for always being straight with him.

Mike goes to Briggs who is lying in bed. He asks if he's up for a run and Briggs says no. He tells Mike not to beat himself up for letting Odin get away. Mike thanks him for saving his life again and tells him that even though he didn't see him he learned a lot about him from the way he fights: that the guy was 6'2", well-built, maybe some military training. He also thinks he broke a few of the guy's ribs. Briggs tells him he's proud of him. Mike leaves. Briggs then rises from bed and looks at his bruised chest in the mirror, grimacing at his broken ribs.

description: Bello's last strike to the Caza Cartel sets a war in motion that Graceland now needs to stop. While on her hunt for Odin, Charlie meets an unusual ally and Briggs comes face to face with the past.
